Cell[TextData[{
 "The simplest setting is in two dimensions, where each vector is specified \
by a pair of numbers. The angle between two vectors gives a good indication \
of how closely aligned they are: if the angle is small, they point in nearly \
the same direction; if the angle is near 90\[Degree], they point in \
completely different directions (they are at right angles). The \
generalization of these ideas to signals (vectors, sequences and images) uses \
the inner product to define the \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]angle.\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] When the inner product is large, the sequences are \
approximately the same (\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]point in the same direction\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]) while if the inner product is zero (if the two are ",
 StyleBox["orthogonal",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ") then they are like two vectors at right angles. Grab either the blue or \
the green arrows and drag. The angle \[Theta] between them changes. When \
\[Theta] is near zero the two vectors point in the same direction. When \
\[Theta] is near 90\[Degree] the vectors are at right angles. The box at the \
right shows how the angle between the vectors x and y can be calculated using \
the inner product <x,y>. "
}], "Text",
